    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I call it a \"goblin trap\" because in the land of embedded systems, a `new` without a `delete` is like summoning a goblin that refuses to leave the room. It doesn't just sit there; it grows, it multiplies, and eventually, it consumes the entire castle (your RAM) until the system collapses. If you ignore the goblin, it will eventually eat your ECU's memory.\n\nNow, back to the `history` vector. This is where the real goblin army is likely hiding. If `history` is a `std::vector<uint8_t>`, every time you call `push_back`, the vector might need to reallocate its internal buffer to make room for the new data. This reallocation is expensive, but the real goblin problem is that you are pushing `len` (the packet size) into a vector that might be growing indefinitely.\n\nIf `history` is meant to store a rolling window of packet sizes, you are likely missing a `pop_front` or a `resize` operation to keep the vector bounded. If you keep pushing without removing old entries, the vector grows forever, and that is a goblin that will never be satisfied.",
